 others. The book pairs the right of privacy for heterosexual sex with queer and proto-feminist crime fiction; racialized police surveillance at midcentury with Black crime fiction; Roe v. Wade (1973) with 1960s and 1970s science fiction; the Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act (1974) with horror; and the right to die with westerns. While we are accustomed to defenses of fiction for its capacity to represent fully rendered private life, Rampell suggests that we might value a certain strand of genre fiction for its capacity to theorize the meaning of the protean concept of privacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aFiction genresxThemes, motives. 0aPrivacy in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aPrivacy.  acrime fiction.  agenre.  ahorror.  alaw and literature.  apost-1945 American literature.  ascience fiction.  awesterns.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363190840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631908/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles